55static int was_et = 0;
56
57static void
58read_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
59{
60 char buf;
61 int len;
62
63 len = recv(fd, &buf, sizeof(buf), 0);
64
65 called++;
66 if (event & EV_ET)
67 was_et = 1;
68
69 if (!len)
70 event_del(arg);
71}
72
73#ifdef _WIN32
74#define LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF AF_INET
75#else
76#define LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF AF_UNIX
77#endif
78
79static void
80test_edgetriggered(void *et)
81{
82 struct event *ev = NULL;
83 struct event_base *base = NULL;
84 const char *test = "test string";
85 evutil_socket_t xpair[2] = {-1,-1};
86 int supports_et;
87
88 /* On Linux 3.2.1 (at least, as patched by Fedora and tested by Nick),
89 * doing a "recv" on an AF_UNIX socket resets the readability of the
90 * socket, even though there is no state change, so we don't actually
91 * get edge-triggered behavior. Yuck! Linux 3.1.9 didn't have this
92 * problem.
93 */
94#ifdef __linux__
95 if (evutil_ersatz_socketpair_(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0, xpair) == -1) {
96 tt_abort_perror("socketpair");
97 }
98#else
99 if (evutil_socketpair(LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF, SOCK_STREAM, 0, xpair) == -1) {
100 tt_abort_perror("socketpair");
101 }
102#endif
103
104 called = was_et = 0;
105
106 tt_int_op(send(xpair[0], test, (int)strlen(test)+1, 0), >, 0);
107 shutdown(xpair[0], EVUTIL_SHUT_WR);
108
109 /* Initalize the event library */
110 base = event_base_new();
111
112 if (!strcmp(event_base_get_method(base), "epoll") ||
113 !strcmp(event_base_get_method(base), "epoll (with changelist)") ||
114 !strcmp(event_base_get_method(base), "kqueue"))
115 supports_et = 1;
116 else
117 supports_et = 0;
118
119 TT_BLATHER(("Checking for edge-triggered events with %s, which should %s"
120 "support edge-triggering", event_base_get_method(base),
121 supports_et?"":"not "));
122
123 /* Initalize one event */
124 ev = event_new(base, xpair[1], EV_READ|EV_ET|EV_PERSIST, read_cb, &ev);
125
126 event_add(ev, NULL);
127
128 /* We're going to call the dispatch function twice. The first invocation
129 * will read a single byte from xpair[1] in either case. If we're edge
130 * triggered, we'll only see the event once (since we only see transitions
131 * from no data to data), so the second invocation of event_base_loop will
132 * do nothing. If we're level triggered, the second invocation of
133 * event_base_loop will also activate the event (because there's still
134 * data to read). */
135 event_base_loop(base,EVLOOP_NONBLOCK|EVLOOP_ONCE);
136 event_base_loop(base,EVLOOP_NONBLOCK|EVLOOP_ONCE);
137
138 if (supports_et) {
139 tt_int_op(called, ==, 1);
140 tt_assert(was_et);
141 } else {
142 tt_int_op(called, ==, 2);
143 tt_assert(!was_et);
144 }
145
146 end:
147 if (ev) {
148 event_del(ev);
149 event_free(ev);
150 }
151 if (base)
152 event_base_free(base);
153 evutil_closesocket(xpair[0]);
154 evutil_closesocket(xpair[1]);
155}
156
157static void
158test_edgetriggered_mix_error(void *data_)
159{
160 struct basic_test_data *data = data_;
161 struct event_base *base = NULL;
162 struct event *ev_et=NULL, *ev_lt=NULL;
163
164#ifdef EVENT__DISABLE_DEBUG_MODE
165 if (1)
166 tt_skip();
167#endif
168
169 if (!libevent_tests_running_in_debug_mode)
170 event_enable_debug_mode();
171
172 base = event_base_new();
173
174 /* try mixing edge-triggered and level-triggered to make sure it fails*/
175 ev_et = event_new(base, data->pair[0], EV_READ|EV_ET, read_cb, ev_et);
176 tt_assert(ev_et);
177 ev_lt = event_new(base, data->pair[0], EV_READ, read_cb, ev_lt);
178 tt_assert(ev_lt);
179
180 /* Add edge-triggered, then level-triggered. Get an error. */
181 tt_int_op(0, ==, event_add(ev_et, NULL));
182 tt_int_op(-1, ==, event_add(ev_lt, NULL));
183 tt_int_op(EV_READ, ==, event_pending(ev_et, EV_READ, NULL));
184 tt_int_op(0, ==, event_pending(ev_lt, EV_READ, NULL));
185
186 tt_int_op(0, ==, event_del(ev_et));
187 /* Add level-triggered, then edge-triggered. Get an error. */
188 tt_int_op(0, ==, event_add(ev_lt, NULL));
189 tt_int_op(-1, ==, event_add(ev_et, NULL));
190 tt_int_op(EV_READ, ==, event_pending(ev_lt, EV_READ, NULL));
191 tt_int_op(0, ==, event_pending(ev_et, EV_READ, NULL));
192
193end:
194 if (ev_et)
195 event_free(ev_et);
196 if (ev_lt)
197 event_free(ev_lt);
198 if (base)
199 event_base_free(base);
200}
201
202struct testcase_t edgetriggered_testcases[] = {
203 { "et", test_edgetriggered, TT_FORK, NULL, NULL },
204 { "et_mix_error", test_edgetriggered_mix_error,
205 TT_FORK|TT_NEED_SOCKETPAIR|TT_NO_LOGS, &basic_setup, NULL },
206 END_OF_TESTCASES
207};
